definition.value: A monogalactosyldiacylglycerol 34:4 in which the 1- and 2-acyl groups are specified as oleoyl and (7Z,10Z,13Z)-hexadecatrienoyl respectively.
A 3-[alpha-D-galactosyl-(1->6)-beta-D-galactosyl]-1,2-diacyl-sn-glycerol in which the 1- and 2-acyl groups are both specified as alpha-linolenoyl.
A 3-[alpha-D-galactosyl-(1->6)-beta-D-galactosyl]-1,2-diacyl-sn-glycerol in which the 1- and 2-acyl groups are both specified as linoleoyl.
A 3-[alpha-D-galactosyl-(1->6)-beta-D-galactosyl]-1,2-diacyl-sn-glycerol in which the 1- and 2-acyl groups are specified as alpha-linolenoyl and hexadecanoyl respectively.
An organic anionic group obtained by deprotonation of the phosphate OH group of 5-thiouridine 5'-phosphate residue; major species at pH 7.3.
An organic anionic group obtained by deprotonation of the phosphate OH group of 5-methyl-2-thiouridine 5'-phosphate residue; major species at pH 7.3.
A phosphatidylglycerol 34:2 in which the 1- and 2-acyl groups are specified as octadecadienoyl and hexadecanoyl respectively.
A phosphatidylglycerol 34:3 in which the 1- and 2-acyl groups are specified as octadecatrienoyl and hexadecanoyl respectively.
A phosphatidylglycerol (18:3/16:0) in which the 1- and 2-acyl groups are specified as alpha-linolenoyl and hexadecanoyl respectoively.
A hydroperoxyoctadecatrienoic acid that is (9Z,11E,14Z)-octadecatrienoic acid in which the hydroperoxy group is located at position 13S.
A member of the class of benzaldehydes in which the hydrogen at position 3 of benzaldehyde has been replaced by a methoxy group.
A member of the class of resorcinols that is phloroglucinol in which one of the phenolic hydrogens has been replaced by a methyl group.
A member of the class of guanidines that is agmatine in which one of the methylene hydrogens adjacent to the primary amino group has been replaced by an allenyl group.
An S-alkyl-CoA having carboxymethyl as the S-alkyl component.
A hexadecanoate ester obtained by the formal condensation of carboxy group of hexadecaoic acid with one of the hydroxy groups of ethylene glycol
A hydroxy monocarboxylic acid anion that is the conjugate base of 12-hydroxyjasmonic acid, obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy group; major species at pH 7.3.
A 5-oxo monocarboxylic acid anion obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy and sulfate groups of 12-sulfojasmonic acid. Major species at pH 7.3
A hydroxy monocarboxylic acid anion that is the conjugate base of 12-hydroxyjasmonic acid, obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy group; major species at pH 7.3.
A 5-oxo monocarboxylic acid anion obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy and sulfate groups of 11-sulfojasmonic acid. Major species at pH 7.3
A 1,3-diglyceride in which both acyl groups are specified as octanoyl.
A 3-(3-sn-phosphatidyl)-sn-glycerol 1-phosphate in which the phosphatidyl acyl groups at positions 1 and 2 are specified as oleoyl and hexadecanoyl respectively.
A dipeptide consisting of an L-aspartyl residue attached to L-glutamic acid via the beta-carboxy group.
An N-acyl-L-alanine resulting from the formal condensation of carboxy group of isovaleric acid with the amino group of L-alanine.
A hydroxyoctadecanoic acid that is octadecanoic acid (stearic acid) in which one of the hydrogens at position 5 has been replaced by a hydroxy group.
An ionic polymer obtained by global deprotonation of the phosphate OH groups of any RNA terminating in a 2',3'-cyclic phosphate. Major structure at pH 7.3
An ionic polymer obtained by global deprotonation of the phosphate OH groups of any RNA terminating in a 2'-phosphate. Major structure at pH 7.3
A cyclic tetrasaccharide constructed from four alpha-glucopyranosyl residues joined by alternate alpha-(1->6)- and alpha-(1->3)-linkages.
A glucotetrose composed of two isomaltose units joined by an alpha-(1->3)-linkage.
A monocarboxylic acid amide that is phenylacetamide in which one of the benzylic hydrogens has been replaced by a hydroxy group.
A dipeptide zwitterion resulting from transfer of a proton from the carboxy to the amino group of any (E)-1-(glycyl-L-cystein-S-yl)-omega-(methylthio)alkylhydroximate; major species at pH 7.3.
A member of the class of chalcones that is trans-chalcone substituted by hydroxy groups at positions 4, 2' and 6', a methoxy group at position 4' and a prenyl group at position 3'.
A member of the class of chalcones that is trans-chalcone substituted by hydroxy groups at positions 2' and 4, methoxy group at positions 4' and 6' and a prenyl group at position 3'.
An aci-nitro compound resulting from the formal tautomerisation of the nitro group of (2-nitroethyl)benzene.
A dipeptide zwitterion resulting from transfer of a proton from the carboxy to the amino group of S-[(Z)-N-hydroxy-2-phenylethanimidoyl]-L-cysteinylglycine; major species at pH 7.3.
A dipeptide zwitterion resulting from transfer of a proton from the carboxy to the amino group of S-[(E)-N-hydroxy-2-(indol-3-yl)ethanimidoyl]-L-cysteinylglycine; major species at pH 7.3.
A dipeptide zwitterion resulting from transfer of a proton from the carboxy to the amino group of Cys(IAN)-Gly; major species at pH 7.3.
An organophosphate oxoanion obtained by removal of four protons from the triphosphate function of glycolaldehyde triphosphate; major species at pH 7.3.
A L-histidine derivative that is ergothioneine in which the thiol hydrogen has been replaced by a hydroxy group.
A 2-methoxyethyl 2-(4-tert-butylphenyl)-2-cyano-3-oxo-3-[2-(trifluoromethyl)phenyl]propanoate that has R configuration.
A 2-methoxyethyl 2-(4-tert-butylphenyl)-2-cyano-3-oxo-3-[2-(trifluoromethyl)phenyl]propanoate that has S configuration.
A nitrile that is acetonitrile in which the methyl hydrogens have been replaced by o-trifluoromethylbenzoyl, p-tert-butylphenyl, and (2-methoxyethoxy)carbonyl groups.

A carboxylic ester resulting from the formal condensation between a carboxylic acid and the hydroxy group of 2-methoxyethanol. In contrast to many other water-solubilising esters, the 2-methoxyethyl esters of many amino acids are crystalline, allowing them to be easily purified.

An organyl group resulting from the formal cleavage of the hydroxy group from 2-methoxyethanol. It is used as a protecting group for carboxylic acids (in contrast to many other water-solubilising esters, the 2-methoxyethyl esters of many amino acids are crystalline, enabling them to be easily purified).
A cyclic tetrapyrrole anion that is the carbanion obtained by removal of the acidic proton from position 21 of pheophytin a. Major species at pH 7.3
A cyclic tetrapyrrole anion obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy groups of nickel-sirohydrochlorin; major species at pH 7.3.
An organic anion that is the carbanion obtained by removal of the acidic proton from position 3 of tenuazonic acid; major speies at pH 7.3.
An organic group derived from any 3beta-hydroxy-Delta(5)-steroid.
